<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=102331533141884></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102331533141884><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=102331533141884>RE: Best newb spells?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=102331533141884#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=151942><span id=Guru>Kelanthor</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>108 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Jun 5th 6:26 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.38]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Greetings,<br><br>Having a fair few spells by lvl 10 can be a bit confusing, and the choice only gets greater as your level does! That said, trying out your spells on yourself (for buffs, heals, etc.) or easily defeated green mobs (for root, direct damage or damage over time spells) will give you some clue as to what they do and how effective they are.<br><br>I'll work backwards from lvl 9, as you should always try to use the best spell in each line. I'll also try not to duplicate anything Tamarask has already mentioned.<br><br>Level 9<br>Tamarask covered all these, but if you're meleeing (and most of us still are at that level, and for a while after) then make sure you have Thistlecoat, Strength of Earth and Firefist active at all times. For tougher mobs, you can also memorise Shield of Thistles and cast that immediately prior to attacking. That's because the first 3 last a fair time(about 10 minutes for Firefist, about 30 for the other two) while SoT will only last a couple.<br><br>Level 5<br>Burst of Fire: Put this to the back of your spellbook, you've got Ignite now...<br>Camouflage: Much underrated spell, but very handy! A kind of invisibility that works against a lot of non-undead creatures and all animals. Very nice for travelling thru zones you're unfamiliar with. Also good for casting just before medding.<br>Cure Disease/Poison: Self-explanatory, although multiple casts may be needed to cure your target.<br>Gate: First of the transport spells - takes you back to your last bind point.<br>Grasping Roots: Nice root and small damage spell. Can be resisted however. If unresisted, holds creature still.<br>Harmony: Another much underrated spell. Lowers the aggro radius of non-undead/animal mobs. This allows you to cast it on several that are close together (it has an area effect) and then pull just one with Snare. If you're close enough, you'll see all the mobs affected emit a slight glow as the spell takes effect.<br>Invoke Lightning: Area of effect DD spell. Note there is a substantial delay (8+ seconds) before you can recast.<br>Ward Summoned: DD spell only effective against summoned creatures.<br>Whirling Wind: DD spell, better damage than Invoke Lightning, not as good as Ignite. Can also stun your target. However, has a 15 sec delay before you can recast.<br><br>Level 1<br>Most of these should have been superceded by better spells, so I'll only mention the ones that are still useful.<br>Dance of the Fireflies: What's this useful for? Raising your Conjuration skill when you level up. Your next DoT spell at lvl 14 is Stinging Swarm, which is also Conjuration - you don't want that fizzling because you didn't bother to keep that skill up to max as you levelled up. Spend a night casting this spell each time you level and you won't have that problem.<br>Endure Fire: Self explanatory.<br>Flame Lick: Why bother? Because it's your only DoT spell until level 14. Also, it debuffs the target's armour class. Us being not the greatest melee class in Norrath, every little helps!<br>Lull Animal: Harmony's better.....<br>Panic Animal: Nice in conjunction with Snare, get the beastie running, then smack it on the bum with your best weapon!<br>Sense Animals: Self-explanatory.<br>Skin Like Wood: Another buff you should have active at all times.<br>Snare: Superb spell - Slows your target down so you can either run away and escape, run away and cast spells at it, or fear it (if an animal) and give it a good hiding.<br><br>I hope this lot's been some help, Shely. As Tamarask suggested, have a look at the spells section on here, or one of the other EQ sites. The info is all there, you just need to dig a bit!<br><br><br>Fight on!<br>&nbsp;<br>Kelanthor<br>Wood Elf Druid of the 41st Circle<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=212672" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=212672</a></td></tr>
