	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102269268089391><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=102269268089391>RE: Why no multi-classing?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=102269268089391#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=117530><span id=Guru>Calabar</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>179 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, May 29th 1:28 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.46]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Another reason for not allowing multi-classing is for game balance.&nbsp;&nbsp;EQ was designed so that different classes would be dependent upon one another to promote player interaction.  Thus each class has at least one thing that makes them desirable.  A druid can SoW, but if he/she wants Clarity then an enchanter is needed.  If each character class could do everything, then there wouldn’t be any reason to have classes.  Though I must admit, I’d love it if my ranger could bind and gate.<br>&nbsp;<br><b>Namir Shadowstalker</b><br>Wood Elf Ranger, 51st Season<br><b>Calabar Silverthorn</b><br>Wood Elf Druid, 51st Season<br><b>Pait Spiritwalker</b><br>Vah Shir Shaman, 50th Season<br><br><b>Seventh Hammer</b></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
