	   <a name=10212928513804></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10212928513804><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=10212928513804>RE: Experience</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=10212928513804#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=151942><span id=Guru>Kelanthor</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>108 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, May 13th 8:36 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.13]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Greetings,<br><br>While levelling up fast is fun, you need to watch a couple of things. First, that your desire to level up doesn't push you up so fast that your skills suffer. Non-trade skills are capped (in case you don't know) at a score of (5 x your level) + 5. So at 9th level, you skills max out at 50. Until you reach 100 in a skill, you won't see the number in the box relating to that skill, but you do see the number in your chat box when you get a skill increase.<br><br>If you drive for max experience, you can find skills lagging 20+ points behind. This makes it tough in combat to hit stuff of your own level. More importantly, if you allow your spell skills (Abjure, Alteration, etc.) to lag behind, you'll be getting a lot of spells fizzling when you really need them.<br><br>The other problem as a spell-caster, if you level too quickly, can be getting money together to buy your latest spells. Money is tight at low levels, but there are ways to make some, if you are a non-twinked character. Skeletons produce bone chips, bats produce bat wings - both very in-demand spell components. Save them up and auction them as stacks - bat wings go for around 2pp per stack in Greater Faydark, bone chips at 5pp/stack in East Commons [Mith Marr server prices]. Spiderling and spider silk also goes well to tailors, as do high-quality cat and bear skins. Save any rat/bear/wolf meat from your kills or from other corpses you find. When you next go to town, buy the equivalent number of loaves of bread and turn them into sandwiches. You'll fail a wee bit when starting out, but not much (sandwiches become trivial to make at between a skill of 20 and 35, depending on the meat) and you can sell them back to the vendor for over double what the bread costs you.<br><br>Look out for those special forages - oak bark, morning dew, etc. You can get a fair bit for them, if you don't intend using them yourself. 3 - 5pp per Morning Dew in Greater Faydark.<br><br>As far as gaining experience goes, while you can get quite good exp soloing, you'll find it shoots up quicker when grouped. You might get more per individual kill as a solo, but your down-time while you recover your mana slows you down. Grouping allows you either to kill more monsters of the same level quicker, or to take on those yellows and reds that will bump up the experience bar in big chunks. I'm not sure of good hunting areas for a 9th level halfling, as I was using Greater Faydark and Crushbone at that level, being a Wood Elf! There must be regions close to Rivervale, and I believe the revamped Misty Thicket, since halflings got new class options, can be hunted until the early teens. Not been there myself, so you'll have to check that out.<br><br>Hope this lot is some help at least and good luck with the search for more power!<br><br><br>Fight on!!<br>&nbsp;<br>Kelanthor<br>Wood Elf Druid of the 41st Circle<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=212672" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=212672</a></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
